  <!-- Article Content -->
  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
      <p>The mythology of creativity is remarkably stable across centuries. There is the genius — the singular, gifted individual who produces breakthroughs that ordinary people cannot. There is inspiration — the bolt from nowhere, the shower epiphany, the dream that solved the problem. There is the suffering artist trope, the idea that creative ability comes bundled with instability, eccentricity, and a difficult relationship with the workaday world. There is the implication, running through all of it, that creativity is either possessed or not — something you have in the way you have eye color, not something that can be developed, trained, or even coherently studied.</p>

      <p>The neuroscience of creativity has been dismantling this mythology piece by piece for about two decades, and the picture that has emerged is simultaneously more mechanical and more available than the mythology allowed.</p>

      <p>Creativity, it turns out, is something the brain does. It does it in a specific way, through specific networks, and the capacity for it varies between individuals in ways that have measurable neural correlates. The most significant recent finding — from a 2025 <em>Communications Biology</em> study analyzing 2,433 participants across ten independent samples in five countries — is that creative ability can be reliably predicted by a single neural signature: the frequency with which the brain switches between two large-scale networks.</p>

      <p>Not genius. Not inspiration. Switching frequency.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="two-networks" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Two Networks</h2>

      <p>To understand the finding, you need to understand the architecture.</p>

      <p>The brain organizes much of its higher cognitive function through large-scale networks — distributed systems of regions that reliably activate together and deactivate together depending on the cognitive task. Two networks are central to the creativity story.</p>

      <p>The <strong>default mode network</strong> (DMN) activates during rest, daydreaming, autobiographical memory, mental simulation, and unconstrained thought. It is the brain in its wandering mode — making associative leaps, connecting disparate memories, generating narrative, imagining possible futures. For a long time, the DMN was considered cognitively unproductive — the network that activates when you're not doing anything useful. This assessment was wrong.</p>

      <p>The <strong>executive control network</strong> (ECN) activates during focused, goal-directed tasks — logical reasoning, working memory, attention management, error monitoring. It is the brain's directed mode: disciplined, evaluative, sequential. Precisely the opposite of the DMN in its orientation.</p>

      <p>These two networks are, in most cognitive contexts, anti-correlated: when one is active, the other tends to be suppressed. They are not supposed to work together. And for most cognitive tasks, this separation is adaptive — you want focused attention when you're solving a maths problem, and you don't want your executive network second-guessing your daydream.</p>

      <p>Creativity, the research now shows, requires both — simultaneously and in dynamic coordination.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"Not genius. Not inspiration. Switching frequency."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="switching-signature" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Switching Signature</h2>

      <p>The 2025 study found that the number of times the brain switches between a DMN-dominated and ECN-dominated state, during rest, reliably predicts divergent thinking ability — the capacity to generate multiple novel and original ideas. And this relationship was independent of general intelligence. IQ did not predict switching frequency. Creativity and intelligence are neurologically distinct.</p>

      <p>The relationship followed an <strong>inverted-U curve</strong>: too little switching (the brain stuck in one mode) predicted low creativity. Too much switching (frantic, disorganized alternation) also predicted lower performance. The sweet spot was balanced, fluid alternation — the brain moving freely between its generative and evaluative modes, neither locked in abstraction nor locked in analysis.</p>

      <p>This makes intuitive sense when you consider what the creative process actually requires. Generation without evaluation produces a lot of ideas, most of them unusable. Evaluation without generation produces nothing new to evaluate. The productive creative state requires the generative mode to supply raw material and the evaluative mode to select, refine, and redirect — and requires these two modes to communicate rather than operate in isolation.</p>

      <p>The best earlier research had shown the same pattern during active creative tasks. This study showed it in the resting brain — suggesting that the capacity for DMN-ECN coordination is a stable individual trait that the brain carries into tasks, not just a transient state it enters under favorable conditions.</p>
    </section>

